"Ros M.D., Marín-Murcia J.P., Aboal M.","Biodiversity of diatom assemblages in a Mediterranean semiarid stream: Implications for conservation",2009,"Marine and Freshwater Research","60","1",,"14","24",,,10.1071/MF07231,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-59849111919&partnerID=40&md5=72ec6ac8cdfeb063feb6a635194a7c65","Laboratorio de Algología, Departamento de Biología Vegetal, Universidad de Murcia, E-30100 Murcia, Spain","Ros, M.D., Laboratorio de Algología, Departamento de Biología Vegetal, Universidad de Murcia, E-30100 Murcia, Spain; Marín-Murcia, J.P., Laboratorio de Algología, Departamento de Biología Vegetal, Universidad de Murcia, E-30100 Murcia, Spain; Aboal, M., Laboratorio de Algología, Departamento de Biología Vegetal, Universidad de Murcia, E-30100 Murcia, Spain","Many semiarid streams are threatened both by human demands and climatic effects (global warming), but little is known about their algal biodiversity and their conservation value, especially in Mediterranean areas. The aim of the present study was to evaluate annual changes in the structure and species richness of diatom communities in runs and pools of an oligohaline, semiarid stream in south-eastern Spain, and their relationship with nutrients and hydrology. The pool substrate was covered most of the time by a yellow-brown coat, mainly composed of diatoms and a few cyanophytes (Leptolyngbya). In the runs, cyanophytes were dominant (Rivularia) and diatoms occurred as epiphytes. The diversity of these diatom assemblages was high, particularly in the pools. Some species were present throughout the year, whereas others showed a bimodal growth pattern. Maximum biomasses were reached in summer in the pools and in autumn in the runs, when levels of phosphorus increased as a result of flooding. Species richness and diversity were correlated with hydrology and sulfate concentrations, whereas biomass (as chlorophyll a and ash-free dry weight) was associated with variations in temperature, conductivity and ammonium. These semiarid streams are refuges of biodiversity, representing habitats reliant on cycles of drought and floods, which should be considered in proposals for their conservation. © CSIRO 2009.","Dynamics; South-eastern Spain","annual variation; biodiversity; community structure; diatom; drought; Mediterranean environment; semiarid region; species richness; stream; Eurasia; Europe; Southern Europe; Spain; algae; Bacillariophyta; Cyanobacteria; Leptolyngbya; Rivularia (cyanobacterium)",,,,,,"Abellán, P., Sánchez-Fernández, D., Velasco, J., Millán, A., Assessing conservation priorities for insects: Status of water beetles in southeast Spain (2005) Biological Conservation, 121, pp. 79-90. , doi:10.1016/J.BIOCON.2004.04.011; Aboal, M., Diatomées des cours d'eau sâumatre, temporaires ou permanentes du SE de l'Espagne. (1988) Bulletin de la Societé Royale Belgique, 10, pp. 48-54; Aboal, M., Alcaraz, F., Barreña, J. A., and Egidos, A. I. (2003a). 'El componente vegetal en los humedales de la región de Murcia. Catalogación, evaluación de la rareza y propuestas de medidas para su conservación.' (Comunidad Autónoma de Murcia: Murcia.)Aboal, M., Álvarez-Cobelas, M., Cambra, J., and Ector, L. (2003b). 'Floristic list of non-marine diatoms (Bacillariophyta) from Iberian Peninsula, Balearic Islands and Canary Islands: 4:Diatom Monographs.' (Ed. A. Witkowski.) (A. R. Gantner Verlag KG: Vaduz.)Baldwin, D.S., Rees, G.N., Mitchell, A.M., Watson, G., Spatial and temporal variability of nitrogen dynamics in an upland stream before and after a drought (2005) Marine and Freshwater Research, 56, pp. 457-464. , doi:10.1071/MF04189; Bartkow, M.E., Udy, J.W., Quantifying potential nitrogen removal by denitrification in stream sediments at a regional scale (2004) Marine and Freshwater Research, 55, pp. 309-315. , doi:10.1071/MF04018; Bengtsson, J., Baillie, S.R., Lawton, J., Community variability increases with time (1997) Oikos, 78, pp. 249-256. , doi:10.2307/3546